<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,289,928]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,289,315]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Abdominal segment X tubiform. Antennae nine-segmented, with segments VIII and IX broadly joined. Fore wings broadened in basal half, distally with parallel margins and with broadly rounded tip; first vein complete, bearing setae; second vein present but ending approximately in the middle of the wing with a distinct terminal seta (
<figureCitation box="[159,244,398,424]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–23" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1758,1782]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,849,1735]" captionTargetId="figure-305@23.[151,1436,849,1735]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 21–23. Sesquithrips rostratus gen. et sp. n. holotype female. (21) dorsal view, mouth cone outlined white; (22) left wings, indicated: distinct seta at distal end of second wing vein; (23) serrate hind margin of left hind wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6796627" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6796627/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
). Fore wings with fringe cilia embedded into wing membrane; duplicated cilia present; wing coupling not assessable. Hind wings distally with posterior margin of wing membrane serrate into small teeth, each carrying a fringe cilium at tip attached on a tiny socket (
<figureCitation box="[660,744,470,496]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–23" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1758,1782]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,849,1735]" captionTargetId="figure-305@23.[151,1436,849,1735]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 21–23. Sesquithrips rostratus gen. et sp. n. holotype female. (21) dorsal view, mouth cone outlined white; (22) left wings, indicated: distinct seta at distal end of second wing vein; (23) serrate hind margin of left hind wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6796627" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6796627/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
). Abdomen without sigmoidal wing retaining setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,289,928]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ulitzka" authorityYear="2022" box="[199,337,506,532]" class="Insecta" family="Rohrthripidae" genus="Sesquithrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[199,337,506,532]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Sesquithrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shows modern tubuliferan character states in combination with plesiomorphic features like ninesegmented antennae and fore wings with longitudinal veins. It therefore is allocated to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ulitzka" authorityYear="2018" box="[1150,1309,542,568]" class="Insecta" family="Rohrthripidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Rohrthripidae</taxonomicName>
. Similar as mentioned for 
<taxonomicName authority="Ulitzka, 2022" authorityName="Ulitzka" authorityYear="2022" box="[321,517,578,604]" class="Insecta" family="Rohrthripidae" genus="Adstrictubothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis box="[321,517,578,604]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Adstrictubothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[526,607,578,604]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[526,607,578,604]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" rank="genus">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, the fringes in 
<taxonomicName authority="Ulitzka, 2022" authorityName="Ulitzka" authorityYear="2022" box="[785,923,578,604]" class="Insecta" family="Rohrthripidae" genus="Sesquithrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis box="[785,923,578,604]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Sesquithrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[933,1014,578,604]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[933,1014,578,604]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" rank="genus">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
are embedded for the most part into the wing membrane (
<figureCitation box="[393,479,614,640]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–23" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1758,1782]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,849,1735]" captionTargetId="figure-305@23.[151,1436,849,1735]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 21–23. Sesquithrips rostratus gen. et sp. n. holotype female. (21) dorsal view, mouth cone outlined white; (22) left wings, indicated: distinct seta at distal end of second wing vein; (23) serrate hind margin of left hind wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6796627" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6796627/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
). Only at the serrate posterior margin of the hind wings are they clearly attached on tiny sockets (
<figureCitation box="[300,385,650,676]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–23" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1758,1782]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,849,1735]" captionTargetId="figure-305@23.[151,1436,849,1735]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 21–23. Sesquithrips rostratus gen. et sp. n. holotype female. (21) dorsal view, mouth cone outlined white; (22) left wings, indicated: distinct seta at distal end of second wing vein; (23) serrate hind margin of left hind wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6796627" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6796627/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authority="Ulitzka, 2022" authorityName="Ulitzka" authorityYear="2022" box="[404,542,650,676]" class="Insecta" family="Rohrthripidae" genus="Sesquithrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis box="[404,542,650,676]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Sesquithrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[550,629,650,676]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[550,629,650,676]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" rank="genus">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nel, Penalver, Azar, Hodebert &amp; Nel" authorityYear="2010" box="[777,898,650,676]" class="Insecta" family="Rohrthripidae" genus="Rohrthrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[777,898,650,676]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Rohrthrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Ulitzka, 2022" authorityName="Ulitzka" authorityYear="2022" box="[954,1144,650,676]" class="Insecta" family="Rohrthripidae" genus="Gemineurothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis box="[954,1144,650,676]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Gemineurothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1151,1230,650,676]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1151,1230,650,676]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" rank="genus">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
with regard to the narrow shape of the wings. Furthermore, the dorsolateral sutures found in members of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nel, Penalver, Azar, Hodebert &amp; Nel" authorityYear="2010" box="[1111,1232,686,712]" class="Insecta" family="Rohrthripidae" genus="Rohrthrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1111,1232,686,712]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Rohrthrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Ulitzka, 2022" authorityName="Ulitzka" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Rohrthripidae" genus="Paralleloalathrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Paralleloalathrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[222,300,722,748]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[222,300,722,748]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" rank="genus">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
at abdominal segment II (see below) are not developed in this new genus. Moreover, 
<taxonomicName authority="Ulitzka, 2022" authorityName="Ulitzka" authorityYear="2022" box="[1243,1381,722,748]" class="Insecta" family="Rohrthripidae" genus="Sesquithrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis box="[1243,1381,722,748]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Sesquithrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="20" pageNumber="21" rank="genus">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is easily distinguished from the latter genus and from 
<taxonomicName authority="Ulitzka, 2022" authorityName="Ulitzka" authorityYear="2022" box="[789,985,758,784]" class="Insecta" family="Rohrthripidae" genus="Adstrictubothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis box="[789,985,758,784]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Adstrictubothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[992,1072,758,784]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[992,1072,758,784]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" rank="genus">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
by the second wing vein, which ends in the middle of the fore wing with a stout terminal seta (
<figureCitation box="[848,932,794,820]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–23" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1758,1782]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,849,1735]" captionTargetId="figure-305@23.[151,1436,849,1735]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 21–23. Sesquithrips rostratus gen. et sp. n. holotype female. (21) dorsal view, mouth cone outlined white; (22) left wings, indicated: distinct seta at distal end of second wing vein; (23) serrate hind margin of left hind wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6796627" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6796627/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,289,928]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,830,856]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name of the new genus derives from the Latin prefix 
<emphasis box="[1003,1073,831,856]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">sesqui</emphasis>
, meaning “one and a half”, and 
<emphasis box="[151,216,866,892]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">thrips</emphasis>
, the usual term for a genus within 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Ulitzka" baseAuthorityYear="2019" box="[605,761,866,892]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Thysanoptera</taxonomicName>
. It refers to the wing venation with a complete first vein and a second vein extending only half the length of the fore wing (
<figureCitation box="[848,933,902,928]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–23" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1758,1782]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,849,1735]" captionTargetId="figure-305@23.[151,1436,849,1735]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 21–23. Sesquithrips rostratus gen. et sp. n. holotype female. (21) dorsal view, mouth cone outlined white; (22) left wings, indicated: distinct seta at distal end of second wing vein; (23) serrate hind margin of left hind wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6796627" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6796627/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
